## Writing instructions

These reference write-ups show the quality and the plain, careful voice to aim for (match
the voice and care, NOT the length — your post should be far shorter than these):
- https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/ghESoA8mo3fv9Yx3E/why-do-some-language-models-fake-alignment-while-others-don
- https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/LqDjxSceFz8tjMe2j/auditbench-evaluating-alignment-auditing-techniques-on

- **Lead with the simplest true framing of the results.** This is the overriding goal; the
  rest of these instructions serve it. Work out the plainest true statement of what was
  found and build the whole post around it. Choose the simplest framing, metric, and example
  that is still faithful to the evidence, and add comparison conditions and caveats only
  after that core is clear. When in doubt, cut a complication rather than add one.
  - Set up the experiment in plain words before using any of its terminology. A reader who
    has not seen the source papers should be able to follow the post on its own; assume they
    have some context on the project proposal but none on what happened during the research.
  - Anchor the main result to one concrete worked example before generalizing: show a
    representative case (a real input and the model's output), then layer on the broader
    claim and the comparison conditions.
  - If the proposal frames the project as a response to a specific prior result, open with
    that context in a sentence — the reader should know what question the headline answers.
  - A reader should be able to restate the main result in two plain sentences using only the
    post. If they cannot, the framing is too abstract or the metrics are underspecified.
  - Don't let the headline outrun the evidence: if the clean result rests on a single case
    or condition, say so in the abstract and framing, not only in a buried caveat.
  - Show the concrete artifacts a reader most wants to see (a representative example, a
    sample input and output), not just summary statistics about them.

- **Structure.**
  - Write a shortform research note, not a paper: roughly 300-800 words, hard cap ~1000.
    Open with a 3-5 bullet TL;DR of the main takeaways (one line each, then a line break),
    then the headline result in a sentence or two, then one short paragraph of setup in
    plain words (defining the key metric), then the one or two figures that carry the
    result, then caveats and limitations. No formal Introduction/Methods/Results
    scaffolding and no appendices; short bold mini-headers or paragraph breaks are fine if
    they help.
  - Headers and bolded lead-ins must state the finding in plain words. No vague taglines
    or slogans ("Belief is trainable", "Less is more") — a header should mean something
    concrete to a reader who reads only the headers.
  - Prose carries takeaways; figures carry numbers. Paragraphs should state what was found
    and what it means, with at most the one or two headline numbers in text — every other
    exact number belongs in a figure, its caption, or a table. If a paragraph is
    accumulating numbers, that's a figure trying to happen.
  - Cut secondary results unless they change the takeaway; one or two sentences may point
    at what else was tried and how it came out.

- **Metrics and terminology.**
  - Define each metric once, in plain language, then reuse one name for it. Don't introduce
    several near-synonymous names for the same underlying quantity; if a quantity is measured
    under different conditions, keep the metric name fixed and vary only the condition.
  - Express an effect one consistent way (e.g. percentage points everywhere, not a ratio in
    one figure and a difference in another).
  - Avoid cryptic or non-standard terminology. Communicate in common words or standard ML
    terms, and define any term that isn't standard English or standard ML on first use, then
    use it consistently. Avoid coinages invented during the research (e.g. "off-manifold",
    "liveness control", "graft", "projection-z") unless you define them; prefer the standard
    term or plain language. Don't give a common word a special private meaning or use one in
    a way a reader could misread — if a term could be read two ways, pin it down or replace
    it. A reader should never have to guess what a word means.
  - No nonstandard hyphenated coinages ("flat-to-stricter", "risk-gated", "emphasis-matched"):
    if the compound isn't a standard term, unpack it into plain words.

- **Anticipate the reader's confusions.** Before finishing, list the ways a careful reader
  could misread the post, and make the text foreclose each one. The recurring offenders:
  - When a model appears in more than one role (trained as a policy, used as a monitor,
    serving as a judge), say which role is meant at every mention where it could be
    misread. "We trained X" must never leave the reader guessing whether X was trained to
    act or trained to evaluate.
  - Chain-of-thought is doubly ambiguous: "reviewing with CoT" could mean the monitor
    thinks out loud, or the policy's CoT is shown to the monitor. Always say whose CoT and
    who sees it.
  - Never call a condition just "the control" or "the baseline": say concretely what it is
    ("the same model before fine-tuning", "the same prompt without the persona framing").
  - Spell out dataset and setup shorthand on first use ("MBPP-derived" → what was derived,
    how).

- **Voice and length.**
  - Be concise. Cut AI filler: throat-clearing, vague hype, hollow contrast ("not just X,
    but Y"), restating the obvious, or padding. Keep only sentences that carry real
    content, in the precise, plain voice of a careful researcher.
  - Write a finished product, not a process log. Don't reference the AI agent doing the
    research; the goal is a polished research shortform a careful researcher would post,
    not a summary of the agent's work.

- **Citing prior work.**
  - When you mention prior work, cite it (author/title + link); only use citations that
    appear in the proposal or that you verified against an artifact in the run — never
    fabricate a reference. A short "References" list at the end is fine.

- **Figures.**
  - One plot per figure: try not to have multiple subplots in a plot.
  - Clean and legible: AI-generated figures usually have too much text on them. Keep labels
    and legends clean and elegant, and push detail into the caption below. Default to small
    figsizes with big, short text.
  - Show uncertainty whenever possible: add error bars (or confidence bands) when the data
    supports them — variation across seeds, prompts, or resamples, or a bootstrap over
    examples — and say in the caption what they represent (e.g. "95% CI over 5 seeds").
    Only omit them when there is genuinely no variation to quantify; never invent them.
  - No clipped or overlapping text: every title, axis label, tick label, legend, and
    annotation must fit fully inside the saved image (use a tight layout /
    `bbox_inches="tight"`, rotate or thin out crowded tick labels). Open the saved .png
    with your Read tool and check it before citing it.
  - No cryptic shorthand anywhere a reader looks (legends, axis labels, titles, tick labels):
    spell out every series, line, or bar fully (short but complete), and replace run-internal
    names (e.g. `cfg3`, `exp_v2`, `kto_sft`, `m1`/`m2`, `acc`, `pp1`) with the plain-English
    thing they stand for ("KTO adversarial training", "accuracy"). If an abbreviation is
    truly unavoidable, define it in the caption. A reader who has never seen the run should
    understand the figure without guessing.
  - Save each cited figure to ./final_plots/ as BOTH .png and .pdf, and reference it with a
    relative path, e.g. `![Fig 1: headline](final_plots/fig1_headline.png)`.

- **Final pass — read the draft from the outside.**
  - Read it as if you had only seen the proposal and nothing else from the run: would you
    follow it on first read? If not, fix it.
  - Don't miss important things the research did that the reader should know about.
